As an introverted creative entrepreneur who values their privacy, running a business shouldn't feel this awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to interact with large tech companies in an extroverted way. Here, to advertise, you have to follow the algorithm, share your personal charm. Get verified on that service, stay online 24/7, use your own videos to answer questions and respond immediately. Video, video, or video.
1/3
For me, this is the year of transformation.
I don't want to pour my money, data, and energy into large tech companies anymore, nor do I want to follow the advice of mentors who only apply single, extroverted solutions to everyone. I'm exploring new business models while also working to overcome my long-held belief that success can only be achieved by doing things in a certain specific way.
Wish me luck!
The first step has been taken.
I've left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deactivated my personal WhatsApp account.
I've left Google Analytics, the last external tracker on my website, and I feel great about it.
I've recently subscribed to a European CRM service in order to better support GDPR, and I will be migrating my business to it over the next few weeks.
I've moved my MX records to Proton, now having full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for basic email verification.
